entry.title: Watch ephemeral network policies enablement
entry.content:
Adds code (EphemeralNetworkPoliciesEnablementHandler) that evaluates the DeviceEphemeralPoliciesEnabled device policy (proxied through a

local_state pref) and the kEphemeralNetworkPoliciesEnabled feature flag.



The new device policy is only evaluated if a newly added

`EphemeralNetworkPoliciesEnabledPolicy` feature (enabled by default)

is enabled.



If any of those is true, the ephemeral network policies feature is

considered to be enabled. This is made available through a new

ash::policy_util::AreEphemeralNetworkPoliciesEnabled() accessor for

easy access from all chromeos/ash/components/network layers (to

be able to DCHECK easily).

entry.title: Add VariableRefreshRateController
entry.content:
This CL creates the VariableRefreshRateController to manage the enabled

or disabled state of the variable refresh rate feature. VRRC observes

the GameMode state, BatterySaverMode state, and relevant feature flags

for determining whether VRR should be enabled. Updates are issued to

the DisplayConfigurator for initiating modesets as needed.



This CL also adds an Observer interface to GameModeController so that

state changes can be subscribed to by VRRC and others.

entry.content:
The enum value UrlLoadStrategy::ALWAYS_IN_INCOGNITO was created to solve

the issue where the user opens tabs from "Context Menu -> History" when

the active tab is incognito. (crbug.com/960728 , with video of original

issue https://drive.google.com/open?id=1pPG2570Mn1-Y8GYplA5y3kguMHjyBd_2)

altogether (OverflowMenuMediator::destinationForDestinationType,

authored by @rkgibson in crrev/c/4602280) so the purpose of ALWAYS_IN_

INCOGNITO url load strategy is now obsolete.



This CL removes this enum to enhance code readability, otherwise future

developers may wonder why ALWAYS_IN_INCOGNITO and ALWAYS_NEW_FOREGROUD_

TAB are mutually exclusive (because they really should not be!)

entry.title: [css-nesting-ident] Stop ConsumeValue at {} when possible
entry.content:
Since braces can no longer appear in standard property values

(except as the whole value), we can early-out of tokenization

if unexpected braces are encountered.



There are two optimization in this CL:



1. ConsumeValue is now split into "ConsumeRestrictedPropertyValue"

and "ConsumeUnrestrictedPropertyValue", with "restrictions"

referring to how '{}' may and may not be used. Standard properties

use the restricted version, and custom properties (and

descriptors) use the unrestricted version (same as before).

This fixes the O(N^2) problem described in [1], because we no

longer tokenize past the '{' after (what was intended as) the

style rule prelude.

2. Then we have the case where '{ ... }' is the whole value.

In this case, we can't just stop at the first '{', but we instead

have to stop after the first block (because nothing is supposed

to follow that block). This prevents unnecessarily tokenizing

stuff after the {} if we're anyway going to restart.



The included performance tests:



- NestingIdentKnownProperty.html: 242ms without this CL,

5ms with this CL.

- NestingIdentLeadingBraces.html: 118ms without this CL,

61ms with this CL.



I also ran the style perf test on a version of this CL which

enables it unconditionally (i.e. drops the runtime flag).

The result is a little strange. Some minor slowdown is to be

expected. I have no good explanation for the result on the Extension

subtest, however.

entry.title: Don't use PDM::SetProfiles..() in AUTOFILL_PROFILE sync tests.
entry.content:
The Autofill team is trying to remove PDM::SetProfiles..(), since:

- It overwrites all profiles stored in the PDM, making it easy to

accidentally wipe the state.

- Contrary to other PDM functions, it first synchronously updates the

PDM's state, before changes are afterwards posted to the DB.

- It skips several consistency checks using a hack called

"enforced modifications".

More details at go/pdm-autofill-table-interface.



All non-test uses of this function were already removed. This CL removes

the remaining uses in AUTOFILL_PROFILE sync integration tests,

unblocking the removal of said function.



In the tests, it turns out that the function is only used to implement

Add/Update/Remove, which can be done in a simpler way using the

appropriate PDM functions.



The logic waiting for the asynchronous operations to complete is

simplified using the PDM test utils.

entry.title: Fix PersonalDataLoadedObserverMock ODR violation
entry.content:
A lot of tests wait for async PDM events to finish, usually by employing

a mock observer for OnPersonalDataChanged().

http://crrev.com/c/4897777 recently tried to unify the redefinitions of

such mock classes, by introducing the personal_data_manager_test_utils.

The test utils are part of test_support, which is linked to unit and

browser tests alike. However, as of right now, the test utils are only

used for components_unittests (namely the PDM unit tests).



http://crrev.com/c/4897277 tried to use them in sync integration tests,

by modifying autofill_helper.cc. This file is somehow also part of

interactive_ui_tests. By including the test utils in autofill_helper.cc,

this causes an ODR violation with the class of the same name in

local_card_migration_uitest.cc (both are in the autofill namespace).

The definitions are not equivalent, since the class used in the card

migration tests doesn't mock OnPersonalDataFinishedProfileTasks(). This

caused the test to crash in an incomprehensible way:

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4897277/13?checksPatchset=10&checksRunsSelected=linux_chromium_asan_rel_ng&tab=checks



This is fixed by using the PersonalDataLoadedObserverMock from the

test utils in local_card_migration_uitest.



Note: There are more definitions of PersonalDataLoadedObserverMock that

can be removed, e.g. in payment_request_browsertest_base or

chrome_browsing_data_remover_delegate_unittest. None of them cause

problems, since they are in different namespaces.

entry.title: Revert "Reapply "[//cc] Add MappableSI path to OneCopyRasterBufferProvider""
entry.content:
This reverts commit f153e55a8dc700f4e04ff95fd48c8c55defe3622.



Reason for revert: Causes flake in blink_web_tests. See

https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=1486067#c24

for an excellent diagnosis. I'll figure out the issue offline and

reland.



Original change's description:

> Reapply "[//cc] Add MappableSI path to OneCopyRasterBufferProvider"

>

> This CL adds a new path to OneCopyRasterBufferProvider that uses

> MappableSharedImage rather than GpuMemoryBuffer. The new path is

> protected by a base::Feature that is disabled by default. The gist of

> the change is that rather than creating a GpuMemoryBuffer, mapping that

> in, and then later creating a SharedImage from it, the new path directly

> creates a MappableSharedImage (via the new CreateSI() entrypoint), maps

> that in, *and* additionally uses it in the same ways that the SI created

> from the GMB is being used.

>

> One subtlety is that the GMB is created with the size of the

> StagingBuffer, while the SharedImage for the StagingBuffer in its

> current creation point in CopyOnWorkerThread() is created with the

> `resource_size` param passed to PlaybackAndCopyOnWorkerThread(). Thus,

> we would want the MappableSI for the StagingBuffer to be created with

> "both" sizes. Fortunately (and as one would expect), the StagingBuffer

> is initialized with the `resource_size` param, so the two sizes are

> guaranteed to be the same [1].

>

> [1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:cc/raster/one_copy_raster_buffer_provider.cc;l=295-297?q=CopyOnWorker&ss=chromium

>

> NOTE: This CL is a reland. The only difference from the original is that

> the base::Feature is disabled rather than enabled while we investigate

> test issues that might have been caused by this CL as well as

> performance regressions flagged by Pinpoint.

>

entry.title: Make pip window UI talk to PictureInPictureWindowManager
entry.content:
Both document and video pip need to differentiate a user-initiated

close operation via the window UI from other causes (e.g., the

site closes the pip window). Previously, video pip would close

the controller directly, while document pip would call the very

much overloaded `ExitPictureInPicture()` on the window manager.



This CL adds a new method to the window manager that indicates

a ui-related close request. It acts similarly to what both previous

methods did: they eventually call `Close()` on the window controller.



This is in preparation for autopip permission embargo, which needs

to treat user-initiated closes separately. One might argue that

all close operations should start in the window controller, but

that's a much bigger change, and less clear. This is a much smaller

change in how close works.
